615.answer:
Mutating an input array surprises callers and creates hidden side effects. Return a new array instead, leaving the original untouched.

Before (mutates input):
```javascript
function normalizeScores(scores) {
  for (let i = 0; i < scores.length; i++) {
    scores[i] = Math.round(scores[i] * 100) / 100;
    if (scores[i] > 100) scores[i] = 100;
    if (scores[i] < 0) scores[i] = 0;
  }
  return scores;
}
```

After (returns new array):
```javascript
function normalizeScores(scores) {
  return scores.map(score => {
    const rounded = Math.round(score * 100) / 100;
    return Math.min(100, Math.max(0, rounded));
  });
}
```

Key changes: replaced the mutating `for` loop with `map`, which always produces a new array. Used `Math.min`/`Math.max` to clamp instead of two separate conditionals. The original `scores` array is never modified. Returned values are identical.

