The strategy pattern defines a family of algorithms, encapsulates each one, and makes them interchangeable at runtime without changing the client code. It separates the behavior from the object that uses it, enabling Open/Closed Principle compliance. For payment processing, different strategies (credit card, PayPal, bank transfer) can be swapped in the payment context without altering the checkout logic.

```javascript
// Strategy interface (implicitly defined by duck typing in JS)
class CreditCardStrategy {
  pay(amount) {
    console.log(`Paid $${amount} via Credit Card.`);
  }
}

class PayPalStrategy {
  pay(amount) {
    console.log(`Paid $${amount} via PayPal.`);
  }
}

class BankTransferStrategy {
  pay(amount) {
    console.log(`Paid $${amount} via Bank Transfer.`);
  }
}

// Context
class PaymentContext {
  constructor(strategy) {
    this.strategy = strategy;
  }

  setStrategy(strategy) {
    this.strategy = strategy;
  }

  checkout(amount) {
    this.strategy.pay(amount);
  }
}

// Usage
const ctx = new PaymentContext(new CreditCardStrategy());
ctx.checkout(100);  // Paid $100 via Credit Card.

ctx.setStrategy(new PayPalStrategy());
ctx.checkout(250);  // Paid $250 via PayPal.

ctx.setStrategy(new BankTransferStrategy());
ctx.checkout(500);  // Paid $500 via Bank Transfer.
```

790.answer:
The factory method pattern defines an interface for creating objects but lets subclasses or implementations decide which class to instantiate. It encapsulates object creation, enabling new types to be added without changing client code. Notification senders for different channels (email, SMS, push) are a classic example: a factory creates the right sender based on a channel type.

```java
// Product interface
interface NotificationSender {
    void send(String message, String recipient);
}

// Concrete products
class EmailSender implements NotificationSender {
    public void send(String message, String recipient) {
        System.out.println("Email to " + recipient + ": " + message);
    }
}

class SmsSender implements NotificationSender {
    public void send(String message, String recipient) {
        System.out.println("SMS to " + recipient + ": " + message);
    }
}

class PushSender implements NotificationSender {
    public void send(String message, String recipient) {
        System.out.println("Push to " + recipient + ": " + message);
    }
}

// Factory
class NotificationFactory {
    public static NotificationSender create(String channel) {
        return switch (channel.toLowerCase()) {
            case "email" -> new EmailSender();
            case "sms"   -> new SmsSender();
            case "push"  -> new PushSender();
            default -> throw new IllegalArgumentException("Unknown channel: " + channel);
        };
    }
}

// Client
public class FactoryMethodDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        for (String channel : new String[]{"email", "sms", "push"}) {
            NotificationSender sender = NotificationFactory.create(channel);
            sender.send("Hello!", "user@example.com");
        }
    }
}
```

791.answer:
The singleton pattern ensures a class has only one instance and provides a global access point to it. In multi-threaded environments, naive singletons can create multiple instances if two threads simultaneously check-and-create. A thread-safe implementation can use a static initializer (guaranteed by the CLR in C#), Lazy<T>, or double-checked locking. Lazy<T> is the idiomatic, thread-safe C# approach.

```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading;

public sealed class Logger {
    // Lazy<T> is thread-safe by default (LazyThreadSafetyMode.ExecutionAndPublication)
    private static readonly Lazy<Logger> _instance =
        new Lazy<Logger>(() => new Logger());

    private Logger() {
        Console.WriteLine("Logger instance created.");
    }

    public static Logger Instance => _instance.Value;

    public void Log(string message) {
        Console.WriteLine($"[{DateTime.Now:HH:mm:ss}] {message}");
    }
}

class Program {
    static void Main() {
        // Multiple threads accessing Logger concurrently
        Thread[] threads = new Thread[5];
        for (int i = 0; i < threads.Length; i++) {
            int id = i;
            threads[i] = new Thread(() => {
                Logger.Instance.Log($"Message from thread {id}");
            });
        }
        foreach (var t in threads) t.Start();
        foreach (var t in threads) t.Join();
        // "Logger instance created." appears exactly once
    }
}
```

