Use the Intl.Segmenter API (or a grapheme-cluster library like graphemer) to split into user-perceived characters, reverse the array, then rejoin. Reversing by code unit (split('')) or code point ([...str]) both break multi-codepoint clusters such as flag emoji (🇺🇸 = U+1F1FA + U+1F1F8), skin-tone modifier sequences (👨‍👩‍👧 ZWJ sequences), or combining diacritics (e + ̈ = ë). Correct implementation:

```js
function reverseGraphemes(str) {
  const segmenter = new Intl.Segmenter();
  const clusters = [...segmenter.segment(str)].map(s => s.segment);
  return clusters.reverse().join('');
}
// reverseGraphemes('Hello 🇺🇸') === '🇺🇸 olleH'
// reverseGraphemes('e\u0308') === 'e\u0308'  // ë kept intact
```
For Node <18 or older browsers use the `graphemer` npm package as a drop-in segmenter.

